I worked that out.  I&#39;ve just released jMock 2.3.0-RC2 that supports JUnit
4.4 and above.  We&#39;ll track JUnit 4 releases from now on to ensure the
latest versions are compatible.

--Nat

On 26/07/07, David Saff &lt;saff@...&gt; wrote:
&gt;
&gt;   Oops. That code will only work in the current 4.5-snapshot. This
&gt; will work in 4.4, 4.5, and beyond:
&gt;
&gt; public static class Mocks extends JUnit4ClassRunner {
&gt; public Mocks(Class&lt;?&gt; klass) throws InitializationError {
&gt; super(klass);
&gt; }
&gt;
&gt; @Override
&gt; protected TestMethod wrapMethod(Method method) {
&gt; return new TestMethod(method, getTestClass()) {
&gt; @Override
&gt; protected void invoke(Object test)
&gt; throws IllegalArgumentException,
&gt; IllegalAccessException,
&gt; InvocationTargetException {
&gt; super.invoke(test);
&gt; verifyMocks();
&gt; }
&gt; };
&gt; }
&gt; }
&gt;
&gt; Thanks,
&gt;
&gt; David Saff
&gt;
&gt;
&gt; On 7/23/07, David Saff &lt;saff@... &lt;saff%40mit.edu&gt;&gt; wrote:
&gt; &gt; Nat,
&gt; &gt;
&gt; &gt; Extending internals of your dependencies in order to give your users a
&gt; &gt; better experience is a fact of life. With 4.4, we took one step
&gt; &gt; toward a more extensible design for JUnit4ClassRunner. In the next
&gt; &gt; version, we hope to finish, and stabilize, the object structure, so
&gt; &gt; that extenders can depend on it. The way to do what you want in JUnit
&gt; &gt; 4.4 and beyond should look like this:
&gt; &gt;
&gt; &gt; public static class Mocks extends JUnit4ClassRunner {
&gt; &gt; public Mocks(Class&lt;?&gt; klass) throws InitializationError {
&gt; &gt; super(klass);
&gt; &gt; }
&gt; &gt;
&gt; &gt; @Override
&gt; &gt; protected TestMethod wrapMethod(Method method) {
&gt; &gt; return new TestMethod(method, getTestClass()) {
&gt; &gt; @Override
&gt; &gt; protected void invoke(Roadie context)
&gt; &gt; throws IllegalArgumentException,
&gt; &gt; IllegalAccessException, InvocationTargetException {
&gt; &gt; super.invoke(context);
&gt; &gt; verifyMocks();
&gt; &gt; }
&gt; &gt; };
&gt; &gt; }
&gt; &gt; }
&gt; &gt;
&gt; &gt; The Roadie class is new in 4.4: it sets up for the test, tears down
&gt; &gt; after the test, and records what&#39;s going on while the test is
&gt; &gt; performing. (For cultural background to the metaphor, see:
&gt; &gt; http://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Roadie)
&gt; &gt;
&gt; &gt; Thanks,
&gt; &gt;
&gt; &gt; David Saff
&gt; &gt;
&gt; &gt; On 7/23/07, Nat Pryce &lt;nat.pryce@... &lt;nat.pryce%40gmail.com&gt;&gt;
&gt; wrote:
&gt; &gt; &gt; Hi all.
&gt; &gt; &gt;
&gt; &gt; &gt; It&#39;s our own fault I know, but the new JUnit 4.4 release breaks jMock
&gt; &gt; &gt; 2 because we extended the internal runner classes to verify mock
&gt; &gt; &gt; objects at the end of the test but before the @After methods are
&gt; &gt; &gt; called to tear down the fixtures.
&gt; &gt; &gt;
&gt; &gt; &gt; The classes we extended no longer exist. What&#39;s the new, approved way
&gt; &gt; &gt; of doing this?
&gt; &gt; &gt;
&gt; &gt; &gt; --Nat
